03843nmm a2200589Ia 9780520919181DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20231996cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209191817 a10.1525/97805209191812doi  a(DE-B1597)568706  a(OCoLC)1202624344  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aBP605.B72bT33 1995 7aREL0170002bisacsh04a299/.932201 aTabor, James D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhy Waco? :bCults and the Battle for Religious Freedom in America /cJames D. Tabor, Eugene V. Gallagher.  aReprint 2020 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2023] 4cÂ©1996  a1 online resource (254 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe 1993 government assault on the Branch Davidian compound near Waco, Texas, resulted in the deaths of four federal agents and eighty Branch Davidians, including seventeen children. Whether these tragic deaths could have been avoided is still debatable, but what seems clear is that the events in Texas have broad implications for religious freedom in America.James Tabor and Eugene Gallagher's bold examination of the Waco story offers the first balanced account of the siege. They try to understand what really happened in Waco: What brought the Branch Davidians to Mount Carmel? Why did the government attack? How did the media affect events? The authors address the accusations of illegal weapons possession, strange sexual practices, and child abuse that were made against David Koresh and his followers. Without attempting to excuse such actions, they point out that the public has not heard the complete story and that many media reports were distorted.The authors have carefully studied the Davidian movement, analyzing the theology and biblical interpretation that were so central to the group's functioning. They also consider how two decades of intense activity against so-called cults have influenced public perceptions of unorthodox religions.In exploring our fear of unconventional religious groups and how such fear curtails our ability to tolerate religious differences, Why Waco? is an unsettling wake-up call. Using the events at Mount Carmel as a cautionary tale, the authors challenge all Americans, including government officials and media representatives, to closely examine our national commitment to religious freedom.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aCultsxUnited States. 0aCultszUnited States. 0aWaco Branch Davidian Disaster, Tex., 1993. 4acomparative religious studies. 4ahistory of the Americas. 4ahistory. 4aliberty. 4areligion. 7aRELIGION / Comparative Religion.2bisacsh1 aGallagher, Eugene V., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520919181?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520919181423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520919181/original  aEBA_EMB  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles